      <p>
        Each cross section of the pyramid is a square;
        this is a sample differential element.
        To determine its area <m>A(x)</m>,
        we need to determine the side lengths of the square.
      </p>

      <p>
        When <m>x=5</m>, the square has side length 10;
        when <m>x=0</m>, the square has side length 0.
        Since the edges of the pyramid are lines,
        it is easy to figure that each cross-sectional square has side length <m>2x</m>,
        giving <m>A(x) = (2x)^2=4x^2</m>.
      </p>

      <p>
        If one were to cut a slice out of the pyramid at <m>x=3</m>,
        as shown in <xref ref="fig_disk0a"/>,
        one would have a shape with square bottom and top with sloped sides.
        If the slice were thin,
        both the bottom and top squares would have sides lengths of about 6, and thus the cross-sectional area of the bottom and top would be about
        <quantity><mag>36</mag><unit base="inch" exp="2"/></quantity>.
        Letting <m>\Delta x_i</m> represent the thickness of the slice,
        the volume of this slice would then be about <m>36\Delta x_i</m> <quantity><mag/><unit base="inch" exp="3"/></quantity>.
      </p>

